Source dictionary for a Plover steno-to-JS/TS shorthand system, parsed by `src/parse.ts` into the actual Plover JSON dictionary. This file is the single source of truth for strokeâ†’snippet mappings; edits here require re-running the parse step to take effect (nothing consumes `dict.steno` directly at runtime).

Format: each entry is a stroke on the opening ` ```` ` fence, then a template on the line(s) before the closing fence. `/`-joined strokes on the fence (e.g. `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT`) mean "root stroke followed by a modifier stroke," used throughout for method-family and type-append lookups. Directives (`@count KEYS`, `@arity N`, `@multiline`, `@fuse`, `@type`, `@noarg`, `@literal`) are bare lines immediately after an entry and bind to the entry above them, not below â€” a directive with no preceding entry is a parse error in `parse.ts`.

Template operators an editor must get exactly right: `%0`-`%9` are tabstop/landing points (plain profile always lands on `%0`); `%d` emits the in-scope count as a literal digit and is never itself a landing point â€” outside a `%[...%]` repeat it's the total repeat count, inside one it's the current iteration index (0-based, i.e. count 3 gives indices 0,1,2, not 1,2,3). `%t` is a type-slot filled later by appending a type stroke (see the `@type` block). `%b` is the one-liner/block-body toggle â€” every `%b` in a single translation flips together, so adding or removing one changes whether the *other* `%b`-marked lines in that same template render as newlines or as nothing; this is why block-body data-structure literals near the bottom use literal `\n` instead of `%b` (they're always multi-line, never toggled). `%p` is a pattern-slot (used sparingly). `%[ sep | body %]` is a repeat construct where `sep` is a joiner never emitted after the last item â€” this is what backs the comma-separated-params entries (`STKWR-PB`, `STKWR-PT`) and the switch-case generator (`STKWR-FP`/`STKWR-FPD`). `%(EXPR)` computes a landing point from a linear expression in `d` (the repeat index) with no renumbering step â€” so `%(2d+1)` and `%(2d+2)` inside `STKWR-FP`'s repeat literally interleave case-labels and case-bodies as separate landable slots per iteration; getting this expression wrong silently misplaces cursor stops rather than erroring. Escape sequences `\n \t \{ \} \% \| \\ \`` must be used for literal versions of those characters inside templates.

Directive semantics that aren't self-evident: `@fuse` (seen throughout the `STKWR-PBGS/*` function family) means the return-type stroke merges directly into the shape stroke, so a fused combo like `func / TPH-FLT` produces a fully-typed function with no intermediate type-less stroke required â€” omitting `@fuse` from a new function-shape entry would force an extra stroke for typing. `@type` marks an entry as a non-standalone type suffix, only valid appended after another stroke (e.g. after `STKWR-PBGS/-FLT`'s `%t` or after `STKWR-T`). `@arity N` (default 0) on a `@type` entry means the type stays non-terminal until N further type-strokes are appended as generic args â€” `Map`, `Record` (arity 2), and `Promise`, `Set`, `Array`, `Generator` (arity 1) all work this way; appending fewer than N leaves the emission incomplete. `@noarg` marks primitive types (`null`, `undefined`, `never`, `function`, etc.) that take no generic args and terminate immediately. `@literal` (used only on the data-structure family under `STKWR-RBGT/*`) means the block is emitted verbatim with no `%0`-style substitution â€” it's whole-class-body text output, and the doc-comment above that section notes the untyped/selector variant is expected to strip every `<T>` and `: T` from these literals, so if you edit one of these class bodies you must keep it structurally strippable to a generic-free version (Trie/TrieNode already has no `<T>` since it's string-keyed only).

`STKWR-T` is the standalone type-emission escape hatch: it emits nothing by itself, but any type stroke appended after it (from the `@type` bank) writes that type free-standing, e.g. for casts/assertions â€” `STKWR-T/PR/STR` produces `Promise<string>`.

Coupling: this file's grammar (fence syntax, all `%`-operators, all directive names/semantics) is normative for `src/parse.ts` â€” if parse.ts's operator handling or directive list drifts from what's described here, the two disagree and one must be fixed to match the other. There is no other schema document.